06107nam a22007215i 9780824862350DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20082008hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248623507 a10.1515/97808248623502doi  a(DE-B1597)484367  a(OCoLC)1024040886  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ9298b.G73 2009 7aREL0070202bisacsh04a294.3/92708209512221 aGrant, Beata, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEminent Nuns :bWomen Chan Masters of Seventeenth-Century China /cBeata Grant. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Brief Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter one. Setting the Stage Seventeenth-Century Texts and Contexts -- tChapter two. Images of Nuns in the Writings of Seventeenth-Century Monks -- tChapter three. The Making of a Woman Chan Master -- tChapter four. Qiyuan Xinggang as Abbess, Dharma Teacher, and Religious Exemplar -- tChapter five. Passing on the Lamp: The Dharma Successors of Qiyuan Xinggang -- tChapter six. From Hengzhou to Hangzhou: Jizong Xingche -- tChapter seven. From Wise Mother to Chan Master: Baochi Jizong -- tChapter eight. Reviving the Worlds of Literary Chan: Zukui Jifu -- tChapter nine. From Beijing to Jiangnan: Ziyong Chengru -- tA Brief Epilogue -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe seventeenth century is generally acknowledged as one of the most politically tumultuous but culturally creative periods of late imperial Chinese history. Scholars have noted the profound effect on, and literary responses to, the fall of the Ming on the male literati elite. Also of great interest is the remarkable emergence beginning in the late Ming of educated women as readers and, more importantly, writers. Only recently beginning to be explored, however, are such seventeenth-century religious phenomena as "the reinvention" of Chan Buddhism—a concerted effort to revive what were believed to be the traditional teachings, texts, and practices of "classical" Chan. And, until now, the role played by women in these religious developments has hardly been noted at all.Eminent Nuns is an innovative interdisciplinary work that brings together several of these important seventeenth-century trends. Although Buddhist nuns have been a continuous presence in Chinese culture since early medieval times and the subject of numerous scholarly studies, this book is one of the first not only to provide a detailed view of their activities at one particular moment in time, but also to be based largely on the writings and self-representations of Buddhist nuns themselves. This perspective is made possible by the preservation of collections of "discourse records" (yulu) of seven officially designated female Chan masters in a seventeenth-century printing of the Chinese Buddhist Canon rarely used in English-language scholarship. The collections contain records of religious sermons and exchanges, letters, prose pieces, and poems, as well as biographical and autobiographical accounts of various kinds. Supplemental sources by Chan monks and male literati from the same region and period make a detailed re-creation of the lives of these eminent nuns possible.Beata Grant brings to her study background in Chinese literature, Chinese Buddhism, and Chinese women’s studies. She is able to place the seven women, all of whom were active in Jiangnan, in their historical, religious, and cultural contexts, while allowing them, through her skillful translations, to speak in their own voices. Together these women offer an important, but until now virtually unexplored, perspective on seventeenth-century China, the history of female monasticism in China, and the contributionof Buddhist nuns to the history of Chinese women’s writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBuddhist nunszChinavBiography. 0aMonastic and religious life (Zen Buddhism)zChina. 0aZen BuddhismzChinaxHistoryy17th century. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486235040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824862350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824862350.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK